{{IAST|'''''Jagadguru'''''}} ([[Sanskrit]]: जगदगुरु), literally meaning the {{IAST|''[[Guru]]''}} of the universe, is a title used in {{IAST|[[Sanatana Dharma|''Sanātana Dharma'']]}}. Traditionally, it has been bestowed upon or used for {{IAST|[[acharya|''Ācāryas'']]}} belonging to the {{IAST|[[Vedanta|''Vedānta'']]}} school (among the [[Sad Darsana|six traditional schools]] of thought in [[Hinduism]]) who have written [[Sanskrit]] commentaries on the {{IAST|[[Prasthanatrayi|''Prasthānatrayī'']]}} (literally, 'the three sources') - the {{IAST|[[Brahma Sutra|''Brahma sūtras'']]}} (the original scripture of {{IAST|[[Vedanta|''Vedānta'']]}}), the {{IAST|[[Bhagavad Gita|''Bhagavad-gītā'']]}} (part of the {{IAST|[[Mahabharata|''Mahābhārata'']]}}) and the principal {{IAST|[[Upanishad|''Upaniṣads'']]}}. Historically, ''Jagadguru''s have established a lineage ({{IAST|[[Parampara|''Paramparā'']]}}), established an institution to spread ''[[Dharma]]'', who have been based in [[Varanasi]], famous for being the centre of [[Sanskrit]] study and the "Capital of All Knowledge". {{Hindu philosophy}} {{Contains Indic text}}
==Origin and history of the term== {{IAST|''Jagadguru''}} is of [[Sanskrit]] origin where जगत् (''jagat'') means 'the entire world' and गुरु (''guru'') means 'spiritual master' (literally, 'dispeller of darkness'). In the classics and scriptures, the word has been used for several [[Deva (Hinduism)|Deva]]s. In the {{IAST|[[Mahabharata|''Mahābhārata'']]}}, [[Arjuna]] addresses {{IAST|Śrī [[Krishna|Kṛṣṇa]]}} as the 'Supreme Master of the entire world'. {{IAST|[[Adi Shankaracharya|Ādi Jagadguru Śrīpāda Śaṅkarācārya]]}} uses the title {{IAST|''Jagadguru''}} for {{IAST|Śrī [[Krishna|Kṛṣṇa]]}} in his {{IAST|''Śrī Kṛṣṇa-āṣṭakam''}}. <ref name="ashtakam">{{cite web|last1=Shankaracharya|first1=Adi|author-link=Adi_Shankara|title=Shri Krishna-ashtakam|url=http://kksongs.org/songs/v/vasudevasutamdevam.html|website=Krsna Kirtana Songs|accessdate=5 September 2016}}</ref> The Sanskrit poet {{IAST|[[Kalidas|Kālidāsa]]}} uses the word {{IAST|''Jagadguru''}} for {{IAST|[[Shiva|Lord Śiva]]}} in his great poem ({{IAST|[[Kāvya|''Mahā-kāvya'']]}}) titled {{IAST|''[[Kumārasambhava]]''}}.<ref>{{IAST|''[[Kumārasambhava]]''}}, Canto 6, Verse 15 and also Canto 8, verse 24.</ref> In the {{IAST|[[Ramcharitmanas|''Rāmacaritamānasa'']]}}, the poet-saint {{IAST|[[Tulasidas|Tulasidāsa]]}} uses the same word for {{IAST|[[Rama|Lord Rāma]]}}.<ref>{{IAST|''[[Rāmacaritamānasa]]''}}, {{IAST|''Āraṇya Kāṇḍa''}}, verse 3.9.</ref> {{IAST|[[Bhaktisiddhanta Sarasvati|His Divine Grace Bhaktisiddhānta Sarasvatī Prabhupāda]]}} uses it for {{IAST|[[Chaitanya Mahaprabhu|Lord Caitanya Mahāprabhu]]}} in his song {{IAST|''Guru Paramparā''}}. <ref>{{cite web|last1=Sarasvati|first1=Bhaktisiddhanta|title=Guru Parampara|author-link=Bhaktisiddhanta Sarasvati|url=http://kksongs.org/songs/k/krsnahoitecatur.html|website=Krsna Kirtana Songs|accessdate=20 April 2016}}</ref> {{IAST|[[A. C. Bhaktivedanta Swami Prabhupada|His Divine Grace A. C. Bhaktivedānta Svāmi Prabhupāda]]}} uses it for {{IAST|Lord [[Krishna|Kṛṣṇa]]}} in his composition {{IAST|''Mārkine Bhāgavata-Dharma''}}. <ref name="kksongs.org">{{cite web|last1=Bhaktivedanta Swami|first1=A.C.|title=Markine Bhagavata-Dharma|author-link=A. C. Bhaktivedanta Swami Prabhupada|url=http://kksongs.org/songs/b/borokrpakoilekrsna.html|website=Krsna Kirtana Songs|accessdate=17 April 2016}}</ref>
==Notable Jagadgurus==
* {{IAST|[[Adi Shankaracharya|Śrīpāda Śaṅkarācārya]]}} ([[Sanskrit]]: {{script|inc-Deva|श्रीपाद शंकराचार्य}}) (A.D. 788-820) (also known as "{{IAST|Ādi Śaṅkara}}" ([[Sanskrit]]: {{script|inc-Deva|आदि शंकर}})), or {{IAST|Śaṅkara Bhagavatpāda}} ([[Sanskrit]]: {{script|inc-Deva|शंकर भगवत्पाद}}): Founder of ''{{IAST|[[Advaita]]}}'' school of ''{{IAST|Vedānta}}''.<ref name="saraswati">{{cite book|last1=Saraswati|first1=Prakashanand|author-link=Prakashanand Saraswati|title=The True History and Religion Of India: A Concise Encyclopedia of Authentic Hinduism|date=2007|publisher=[[Macmillan Publishers]]|isbn=0230630650|url=https://books.google.co.in/books/about/The_True_History_and_the_Religion_of_Ind.html?id=IhLN2I9yTTkC|edition=First|location=New Delhi|accessdate=28 April 2016}}</ref> * {{IAST|[[Ramanujacharya|Śrīpāda Rāmānujācārya]]}} ([[Sanskrit]]: {{script|inc-Deva|श्रीपाद रामानुजाचार्य}}) (1017-1137): Wrote ''{{IAST|Śrībhāṣya}}'', commentary on ''{{IAST|Brahma Sūtra}}''. He also established ''{{IAST|[[Vishistadvaita|Viśiṣṭādvaita]] Siddhānta}}''.<ref name=saraswati /> * {{IAST|[[Nimbarkacharya|Śrī Nimbārkācārya]]}} ([[Sanskrit]]: {{script|inc-Deva|श्री निम्बार्काचार्य}}): Founder of ''{{IAST|[[Dvaitadvaita]]}}'' school of ''{{IAST|Vedānta}}''.<ref name=saraswati /> * {{IAST|[[Madhvacharya|Śrīpāda Madhvācārya]]}} ([[Sanskrit]]: {{script|inc-Deva|श्रीपाद मध्वाचार्य}}) (1239-1319): Founder of the ''{{IAST|[[Dvaita]]}}'' school of ''{{IAST|Vedānta}}''.<ref name=saraswati /> * {{IAST|[[Kripalu Maharaj|Śrī Kṛpālu Ji Mahārāja]]}} ([[Sanskrit]]: {{script|inc-Deva|श्री कृपालु जी महाराज}}) (5 October 1922&nbsp;– 15 November 2013):<ref>{{cite news|title=Spiritual Guru Jagadguru Kripalu Maharaj passes away|url=http://zeenews.india.com/news/nation/spiritual-guru-jagadguru-kripalu-maharaj-passes-away_890031.html|accessdate=12 June 2015|newspaper=[[Zee News]]|date=15 November 2013}}</ref> He received the title of Jagadguru at the age of 34 from Kashi Vidvat Parishad (the oldest and most recognised body of [[Varanasi|Varanasi's]] intellectuals) on Makar Sankranti day, 14 January 1957.<ref name=saraswati /><ref name="encyclopedia">{{cite book|last1=Melton|first1=J. Gordon|author-link=J. Gordon Melton|title=[[The Encyclopedia of American Religions]]|date=2003|publisher=[[Gale (publisher)|Gale]]|isbn=978-0-7876-9696-2}}</ref><ref name=Singh>{{cite web|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2007/20070128/edit.htm#4|title=Varanasi seer’s memory is phenomenal|author-link=Khushwant Singh|last=Singh|first=Khushwant|date=28 January 2007|work=[[The Tribune (Chandigarh)|The Tribune]]|publisher=[[Tribune India]]|accessdate=12 June 2015}}</ref> He was awarded the title {{IAST|''Samanvayācārya''}}, i.e., He analyses and reconciles meaning of all the scriptures, the [[Sad Darsana|six philosophies]] and the (seemingly contradictory) teachings of the other four previous {{IAST|''Jagadgurus''}}.<ref>{{cite web|title=Nikhildarshan-Samanvayacharya|url=http://jkpliterature.org/ShriMaharajJi/NikhildarshanSamanvayacharya.aspx|website=jkpliterature|accessdate=31 May 2016}}</ref> {|Style="margin": "0 auto;" |+'''Original Jagadgurus''' |[[File:Raja Ravi Varma - Sankaracharya.jpg|thumb|Adi Jagadguru Shripada Shankaracharya.|180x180px]] |[[File:Ramanujacharya.jpg|thumb|Jagadguru Shripada Ramanujacharya.|180x180px]] |[[File:Nimbarkacharya's holy icon at the Ukhra Nimbarka Peeth Mahanta Asthal(West Bengal).JPG|thumb|Jagadguru Shri Nimbarkacharya's holy icon.|180x180px]] |[[File:Shri Madhvacharya.jpg|thumb|Jagadguru Shripada Madhvacharya.|180x180px]] |[[File:Kripalu Ji Maharaj Giving Lecture.jpg|thumb|Jagadguru Shri Kripalu Ji Maharaj.|180x180px]] |} ==References== {{Reflist}}
