==Amos, son of Amos==
According to the [[Book of Mormon]], Amos was a [[Nephite]] record keeper.  His father was [[Amos, son of Nephi|Amos]], and his grandfather was [[Nephi the Disciple]].  [[Mormon]] is thought to have abridged his record which consists of 26 verses in the [[Fourth Nephi|Book of 4th Nephi]].<ref>{{lds|4 Nephi|4_ne|1}}</ref>  Amos must have been exceptionally long-lived, for he had custody of the Nephite records for 112 years, approximately from AD  194 to 306 (although a certain commentator<ref>[[Brant Gardner]], [http://frontpage2000.nmia.com/~nahualli/LDStopics.htm 4 Nephi 1]  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090125183304/http://frontpage2000.nmia.com/~nahualli/LDStopics.htm |date=January 25, 2009 }}</ref> suggests that this Amos may be referring to at least two different people). {{Sourcetext|source=Book of Mormon|version=1981|book=4 Nephi|chapter=1|verse=21|range=-46}} are an abridgment of his writings. When Amos died, his brother [[Ammaron]] took over as record keeper.

Amos' record relates the degeneration of the society of the Nephites after the appearance of [[Jesus]] on the American continent.  This degeneration is due to the [[Nephite pride cycle|pride of the people]].

